:Arial; font-size:12pt">9.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Office of Rail Regulation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Draft Determination</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has made provision for a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£67</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> million</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fund to enable Network Rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to deliver a plan to maximise the reduction in risks of accidents at level crossings over and above meeting its existing legal obligations in this respect.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ffice of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">egulation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will publ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ish its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> final Determination on 31 October 2013.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">10.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Department understands that a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level crossing fund </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">comprising an additional £10 million </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be made available by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scottish Ministers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to support Network Rail, local a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uthorities and other local stakeholders in facilitating the closure of level crossings in Scotland.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">11.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With funding from the Department, and as part of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the RSSB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (formerly the Rail Safety &amp; Standards Board) rail industry research programme, Network Rail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has also participated in a project to extend existing industry risk management models to level crossings.  The resulting All Level Crossings Risk Model (“ALCRM”) has further improved Network Rail’s ability to manage the risk to level crossing users, passen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gers and rail staff by targeting those crossings with the highest risk for remedial measures.  The ALCRM</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, in conjunction with further risk recognition and assessment work,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an important element</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in identifying those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> level crossings where funding will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> provide the most substantial safety improvements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over 2014-19</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Network Rail giving sufficient priority to improving safety at level crossings?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">12.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to avoid new level crossings being built due to the associated safety and convenience issues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and to close existing level crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">so far as is reasonably practicable.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">13.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, it would not be proportionate, or practical, to remove all existing cr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">put in place a significant program</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of 19 projects designed to enhance level crossing risk management </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and reduce level crossing risk.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail has also set itself challenging </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">targets for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reducing level crossing risk by 25</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">% by the end of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">March 2014 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and a further 50% by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">March 2019</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department believes that these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">targets and initiatives, together with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ring-fenced funding Network Rail is likely to receive fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r 2014-19</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, mean that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it will be able to give </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sufficient priority </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to impr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oving safety at level crossings.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Government policy and regulatory action by the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in relation to safety at level crossings adequate? What more should the Government and ORR do?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Department will consider any recommendations the Committee makes in this area in due course.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> should the legislation governing level crossings be updated?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department recognises that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">current law on level crossings is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">antiquated, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">comple</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">x an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d inaccessible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For this reason the Department, in collaboration with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ffice of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">egulation, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">put forward a proposal to the Law Commission for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">comprehensive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">review of level crossing legislation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In June 2008, the Law Commission announced tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t this review would take place </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as part of its 10th programme of law reform.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Following public consultation, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Law </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Commission expects to publish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">its recommendations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> later in 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department, together with the Office of Rail Regulation, will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">need to consider the Law Commission’s proposals in detail before responding.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> should public awareness of safety at level crossings be improved?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition to making physical and other changes to level crossings in order to make them safer, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">twork Rail is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">already</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> doing a great deal to improve public awareness of safety at level crossings.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Examples of this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> work include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the on-going national television, radio and on-line “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Don’t Run The Risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” campaign;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the on-going</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Rail Life</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” campaign</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> aimed at primary and secondary school pupils;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">holding awareness events at over 100 level crossings during Internationa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l Level Crossing Awareness Day </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (7 May)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; and </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> recruitment of over 100 dedicated Level Crossing Managers whose roles include </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">building relationships with authorise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d users and the wider community.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department believes that Network Rail’s strategy provides comprehensive coverage but wou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ld welcome the Committee’s recommendations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on how public awareness could be further impr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oved.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Investigation Into The Safety Of Automatic Open Level Crossings On Network Rail’s Managed Infrastructure, Rail Accident Investigation Branch, Report 12/2011, July 2011.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Avai</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">lable from </span><a href="http://www.raib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/110728_R122011_AOCLs_Class_Inv.pdf"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.raib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/110728_R122011_AOCLs_Class_Inv.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The High Level Output Specification (2012): Railways Act 2005 Statement, available from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/3641/railways-act-2005.pdf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Periodic Review 2013: Draft Determination of Network Rail’s Output and Funding for 2014-19, available from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">www.rail-reg.gov.uk/pr13/PDF/pr13-draft-determination.pdf</